statgraphics.eda
Class TimeSeriesPlot

java.lang.Object
  statgraphics.GraphicalAnalysis
      statgraphics.eda.TimeSeriesPlot

public class TimeSeriesPlot
extends GraphicalAnalysis

Generates a time series plot.


Example:
int [][][] time = new int[2][12][6];
data = new double[2][12];
dataNames = {"Company A", "Company B"};
for(int j = 0; j < 2; j++)
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 12; i++)
    {
       time[j][i][0] = 0;
       time[j][i][1] = 0;
       time[j][i][2] = 0;
       time[j][i][3] = 1;
       time[j][i][4] = i + 1;
       time[j][i][5] = 2005;
       data[j][i] = 100 + Math.random() * 20.0;
    }
}

// Multiple time series
pf = new PlotFrame("Time Series Plot I",
    new TimeSeriesPlot(dataNames, "Time Series Plot", "Date", "Stock Price", time, data).plot, 500, 270);

// Single time series
pf = new PlotFrame("Time Series Plot II",
    new TimeSeriesPlot(dataNames[0], time[1], data[0]).plot, 500, 270);

// Another way to generate the time series plot
// Multiple time series
Hashtable argument = new Hashtable();
argument.put(DATA_NAMES, dataNames);
GraphicalAnalysis graphicalAnalysis = new TimeSeriesPlot(argument, time, data).graphicalAnalysis;
JFreeChart myPlot = (JFreeChart) graphicalAnalysis.output.get("PLOT");
pf = new PlotFrame("Time Series Plot III", myPlot, 500, 270);

// Single time series
argument.put(DATA_NAMES, dataNames[0]);
argument.put(TITLE, "Time Series Plot");
argument.put(XLABEL, "Date");
argument.put(YLABEL, "Stock Price");
pf = new PlotFrame("Time Series Plot IV",
    new TimeSeriesPlot(argument, time[0], data[1]). graphicalAnalysis.getPlot(), 500, 270);

// Places the plot frame in a container
new PlotFrameFactory().putPlotFrame(pf);

TimeSeriesPlot

public TimeSeriesPlot(java.util.Hashtable argument,
                      java.lang.Object... dataObject)
Creates a new time series plot given the input arguments and data.

Parameters:
argument - the arguments with the following choices,
DATANAMES, TITLE, XLABEL, YLABEL: complete list of arguments;
DATANAMES: the default title "Time Series Plot", x-label "Time", and y-label "Value".

dataObject - the input collection of time series and dates assoicated with the collection of time series.
Throws:
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - wrong input argument(s) or data.
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - the number of time series should be equal to the one of the associated dates.
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - the length of the data series should be equal to the one of the associated dates.
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - the length of the time vector should be equal to 6.
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - the number of data series should be equal to the number of data names.

TimeSeriesPlot

public TimeSeriesPlot(java.lang.String[] dataNames,
                      java.lang.String title,
                      java.lang.String xLabel,
                      java.lang.String yLabel,
                      int[][][] time,
                      double[]... data)
Creates a new time series plot with the specified names of the data series, title, and labels for the x-coordinate and y-coordinate.

Parameters:
dataNames - the names of the data series,
dataNames[j]: the name of the (j+1)'th time series.
title - the plot title.
xLabel - the label for the x-coordinate.
yLabel - the label for the y-coordinate.
time - the dates assoicated with the collection of time series,
time[j][i][0]: the second (0-59) associated with the i'th data of the j'th time series;
time[j][i][1]: the minute (0-59) associated with the i'th data of the j'th time series;
time[j][i][2]: the hour (0-23) associated with the i'th data of the j'th time series;
time[j][i][3]: the day (1-31) associated with the i'th data of the j'th time series;
time[j][i][4]: the month (1-12) associated with the i'th data of the j'th time series;
time[j][i][5]: the year (1900-9999) associated with the i'th data of the j'th time series.
data - a collection of time series, data[j]: the (j+1)'th data series.
Throws:
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - the number of time series should be equal to the one of the associated dates.
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - the length of the data series should be equal to the one of the associated dates.
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - the length of the time vector should be equal to 6.
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - the number of data series should be equal to the number of data names.
